CHAPTER TWENTY ONE That was a long night for Cora Madison , and the morning found her yellow . 
Cora , drumming with her fingers upon a window in the owl haunted cell , made noises with her throat , her breath and her lips not unsuggestive of a sputtering fuse . 
Now what in thunder do YOU want ? she inquired of an elderly man who turned in from the sidewalk and with serious steps approached the house . 
Pryor , having rung , found himself confronted with the lady he had come to seek . 
Ensued the moment of strangers meeting invisible antennae extended and touched at the contact , Cora's drew in , and she looked upon him without graciousness . 
I just called , he said placatively , smiling as if some humour lurked in his intention , to ask how your father is . 
I heard downtown he wasn't getting along quite so well . 
He's better this morning , thanks , said Cora , preparing to close the door . 
I thought I'd just stop and ask about him . 
I heard he'd had another bad spell kind of a second stroke . 
That was night before last . 
The doctor thinks he's improved very much since then . 
The door was closing he coughed hastily , and detained it by speaking again . 
